{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b44e795c-3df5-4c27-ab00-a3ea1ec79112","content":"There are two approaches — one requires a project, the other doesn't:\n\n## 1. Query MSBuild properties directly (needs a `.csproj`)\n\nFrom a MAUI Android project directory, MSBuild can evaluate the exact values the SDK will use at build time:\n\n```bash\ndotnet msbuild YourApp.csproj -getProperty:AndroidSdkBuildToolsVersion\ndotnet msbuild YourApp.csproj -getProperty:AndroidCommandLineToolsVersion\ndotnet msbuild YourApp.csproj -getProperty:TargetPlatformVersion   # API level\n```\n\nYou can also dump all Android-related properties at once:\n\n```bash\ndotnet msbuild YourApp.csproj -target:_ResolveAndroidSdkPath -verbosity:diagnostic \\\n  | grep -E '(BuildTools|CommandLineTools|PlatformTools|TargetPlatform)'\n```\n\n## 2. Inspect the workload manifest (no project needed)\n\n```bash\n# 1. Find your SDK's Android workload manifest\nDOTNET_ROOT=$(dotnet --info | grep 'Base Path' | awk '{print $3}' | sed 's|/sdk/.*||')\nBAND=$(dotnet --version | sed 's/\\.[0-9]*$/.*/') # e.g. 9.0.100-*\nls \"$DOTNET_ROOT\"/sdk-manifests/*/microsoft.net.sdk.android/\n\n# 2. Read WorkloadManifest.json — it lists pack IDs and versions\ncat \"$DOTNET_ROOT\"/sdk-manifests/<band>/microsoft.net.sdk.android/WorkloadManifest.json\n\n# 3. The resolved pack lives here and contains the MSBuild .targets\n#    that hard-code the required Android SDK component versions:\nls \"$DOTNET_ROOT\"/packs/Microsoft.Android.Sdk.*/\n```\n\nInside the pack's `targets/` directory, look at **`Microsoft.Android.Sdk.DefaultProperties.targets`** (or similar). It sets the canonical values:\n\n- `AndroidSdkBuildToolsVersion` → e.g. `35.0.0`\n- `AndroidCommandLineToolsVersion` → e.g. `13.0`\n- `JavaSdkVersion` → e.g. `17.0`\n- Target API level (`android-XX`)\n\n## CI one-liner (recommended)\n\nCreate a throwaway project and query it:\n\n```bash\nmkdir /tmp/probe && cd /tmp/probe\ndotnet new maui -n Probe --no-restore\ndotnet msbuild Probe/Probe.csproj -getProperty:AndroidSdkBuildToolsVersion \\\n  -getProperty:AndroidCommandLineToolsVersion \\\n  -getProperty:TargetPlatformVersion \\\n  -p:TargetFramework=net9.0-android\n```\n\nThis is the most reliable method — it reflects the **exact** versions your SDK will demand at build time, not documentation that may be stale.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"908ec566-19ee-4b0e-950d-5073db73046a","outputTokens":723,"requestId":"A432:1D28CE:4A5649:56A355:69F00607"},"id":"d764ad9d-adbc-468f-ab08-bc74d5b88b19","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:57:58.611Z","parentId":"13aa1d53-cefd-4d54-9ae8-dcc0d3134257"}
